Qadiriyya]] silsila in sub-continent(Now Punjab,Pakistan).His Spirtual leader and \"Murshid\" was Syed Shah Maroof Khushabi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mufti Ghulam Sarwar Lahori|first=|url=http://archive.org/details/Khazinat-ul-asfiyaurduTranslation4Volumes|title=Khazinat-ul-Asfiya (Urdu translation)  volume 1 Page 254|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 881\">{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook&usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 881|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> He spent his whole live in devotion and love for Allah.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |SHAH SULEMAN\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |SAKHI BADSHAH,NOORI HAZOORI\n|-\n!Born\n|9TH RABI UL AWAL 1508\n|-\n!Residence\n|Purana Bhalwal Tehsil Bhalwal District Sargodha\n|-\n!Died\n|27TH RAMZAN UL MUBARIK FRIDAY NIGHT 1604\n|-\n!Major [[shrine]]\n|Purana Bhalwal Tehsil Bhalwal\n|-\n![[Calendar of saints|Feast]]\n|6th and 7th Muharram\n|-\n!Predecessor\n|SYED SHAH MAROOF\n|-\n!Successor\n|HAJI MUHAMMAD NAUSHA GANJ BAKSH\n|}\n\n= Birth & Parents =\nSAKHI SHAH SULEMAN father's name was Abdullah<ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 881\"/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mufti Ghulam Sarwar Lahori|first=|url=http://archive.org/details/Khazinat-ul-asfiyaurduTranslation4Volumes|title=Khazinat-ul-Asfiya (Urdu translation)  volume 1 page 254|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> who was also a kind and noble man and follower of Syed Shah Maroof Khushabi.His mother name was \"BIBI Bhaag Bhari\" she was also so generous and kind. Sakhi Shah Suleman was born on 9th Rabi ul Awal 1508.<ref name=\":0\" /> His Family lineage belongs to [[Quraysh]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n= EARLY LIFE & EDUCATION =\nHe got his early education from his parents. Shah Maroof used to visit Abdullah\"s house.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 882|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> When Sakhi Shah Suleman was 4 years old he became the eye star of Shah Maroof.His Spirtual progress started in his childhood.\n\n= PERSONAL LIFE =\nSAKHI SHAH SULEMAN HAD TWO WIVES:\n\n# BIBI ROMAL KHATUN\n# BIBI JAURANA KHATUM<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 904|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== SONS ===\nHE HAD TWO SONS\n\n# RAHEEM DAAD\n# TAAJ MEHMOOD<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 905-6|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n= Family Lineage =\n\n===== KA'AB UL QARSHI\u2192MARAA\u2192QULAB\u2192QASSA\u2192ABDUL UL AZA\u2192 ASAD \u2192MUTLIB\u2192 ASAD\u2192 AMEER AYAZ\u2192 AMEER ABDUR REHMAN\u2192 AMEER ABDUR RAHEEM\u2192 MAROOF\u2192 ABDUL A'ALA\u2192 ABDUL UL SHAKOOR \u2192ADAM\u2192 MAZHAR \u2192ISMAEL\u2192 QASIM\u2192 AON\u2192 SULTAN ALI\u2192 KHUDA YAR\u2192 ABDUL KHALIQ\u2192 SHEIKH HUSSAIN \u2192MUHAMMAD SALEH\u2192 MUHAMMAD MURAD\u2192 SHAMS UDDIN\u2192 JALAL UDDIN \u2192ABDULLAH \u2192 SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN NOORI HAZOORI<ref name=\":0\" /> =====\n\n== SIMILARTIY ==\nTHE FAMILY LINEAGE OF [[Bahauddin Zakariya]] MULTANI AND SAKHI SHAH ARE SAME\n\nTHEIR FAMILY LINEAGE BECOME DIFFERENT FROM SONS OF ABDUR RAHEEM BIN ABDUR REHMAN\n\n= SPIRTUAL LINEAGE =\nHE GOT HIS SPIRTUAL TEACHINGS FROM SHAH MAROOF KHUSHABI\n\nHE BELONGED TO SILSILA E QARIYYA AS BELOW:\n\n* [[Muhammad]]\n* [[Ali]]\n* [[Hasan al-Basri]]\n* [[Habib al-Ajami]]\n* [[Dawud Tai]]\n* [[Maruf Karkhi]]\n* [[Sirri Saqti]]\n* [[Junayd of Baghdad]]\n* [[Abu Bakr Shibli]]\n* [[Abdul Aziz bin Hars bin Asad Yemeni Tamimi]]\n* [[Abu Al Fazal Abdul Wahid Yemeni Tamimi]]\n* [[Mohammad Yousuf Abu al-Farah Tartusi]]\n* [[Abul Hasan Hankari]]\n* [[Abu Saeed Mubarak Makhzoomi]]\n* [[Abdul Qadir Gilani]]\n* SYED ABDUL WAHAB GILANI\n* SYED ABDUL SALAM GILANI\n* SYED AHMAD GILANI\n* SYED MASOOD GILANI\n* SYED ALI GILANI\n* SYED SHAH MEER GILANI\n* SHAMS UDDIN GILANI\n* SHAH MUHAMAMD GHOAS GILANI\n* SYED MUBARIK HAQANI\n* SHAH MAROOF\n* SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN NOORI HAZOORI<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n= TEACHINGS AND CHARACTERISTICS =\nWHEN SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN NOORI HAZOORI received THE \"KHILAFAT\",HE was ordered by his murshid to travel different places.So he travelled [[Shahpur]],[[Khushab]],[[Chawa]],Deowal,Jukali, TAKHT HAZAARA,KASHMIR AND GUJRAT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 887|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Thousand of non Muslims became Muslims on his hands.After travel,his sheikh ordered him to reside in Purana Bhalwal (Now in tehsil Bhalwal,District Sargodha).Thousand of people from surrounding found straight way from them.\n\nSAKHI SHAH SULEMAN was strict follower of Shariat and Sunnat e Muhummad.He spent his mostly time in mosque in remembrance of Allah\n\nHe was so generous that he got the title of \"Sakhi\" .He was very kind to poors and needy ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 892|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n= SUCCESSORS =\nTHERE ARE MANY SUCCESSORS OF SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN NOORI HAZOORI.SOME OF THEM ARE KNOWN AND SOME ARE UNKNOWN<ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 906\">{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 906|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHIS KNOWN SUCCESSORS ARE FOLLOWING:\n\n[[Muhammad Qadiri]]: HE WAS SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN BELOVED SUCCESSORS WHICH FOUNDED THE NAUSHAYIA QADRIA SILSILA\n\nRAHEEM DAD : HE WAS THE ELDER SON OF SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN\n\nTAJ MEHMOOD: HE WAS THE YOUNGER SON OF SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN\n\nMULLAH KAREEM UDDIN JOKALVI\n\nDEWAN ABU AL FATAH KANBOHI\n\nMULLAH GHAZI GONDAL BHALWALI\n\nSHEIKH HAMMO FAQEER\n\nSHEIKH HINDI<ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 906\"/>\n\n= SHRINE =\n[[File:HAZRAT SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN 2.jpg|thumb|DARBAR SHARIF SAKHI SHAH SULEMAN NOORI HAZOORI]]\nSAKHI SHAH SULEMAN SHRINE IS LOCATED IN PURANA BHALWAL,TEHSIL BHALWAL, DISTRICT SARGODHA<ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 912\">{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1K2UBi_PY2EhAuVukqHmr89ZxpyN6IDau/view?usp=embed_facebook|title=\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 912|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Docs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qadri-naushahi.com/Awliya/Genealogy2.html|title=Genealogy & Spiritual Lineage No. 25|last=|first=|date=|website=www.qadri-naushahi.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auqaf.punjab.gov.pk/shrines#sargodha|title=Shrines {{!}} Auqaf & Religious Affairs Department|website=auqaf.punjab.gov.pk|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Darbaar+Sakhi+Shah+Sulman+Noori+Hazoori/@32.2730345,72.8739842,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x3921a295ec3eff79:0x91434f6ac5759c18!8m2!3d32.2728078!4d72.8745575?shorturl=1|title=Darbaar Sakhi Shah Sulman Noori Hazoori|website=Darbaar Sakhi Shah Sulman Noori Hazoori|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n= DEATH =\nSAKHI SHAH SULEMAN DIED ON NIGHT OF FRIDAY 27TH RAMZAN UL MUBARIK 1604.HE DIED AT THE AGE 98 YEARS<ref name=\"\u0634\u0631\u06cc\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0648\u0627\u0631\u06cc\u062e \u062c\u0644\u062f 1.pdf Page 912\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n[[Category:Sufism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sufism]]\n[[Category:Islam-related lists]]\n[[Category:Qadiri order]]\n__INDEX__\n__INDEX__\n[[Category:Sufism]]\n[[Category:Sufism in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Qadiri order]]\n[[Category:Islam-related lists]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "Saadulhassan2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shah_Sulaim%C4%81n_N%C5%ABri"}
{"title_page": "Nigeria Centre for Disease Control", "text_new": "{{short description|Health agency in Nigeria}}\n'''Nigeria Centre for Disease Control''' is Nigeria's leading [[National public health institutes|national public health institute]]. The NCDC is a Nigerian federal government agency under the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)]] and is headquartered in [[Abuja]], [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/apo/nigeria-centre-for-disease-control-world-health-organization-ncdcwho-map-resources/dw1ey3x|title=Nigeria Centre for Disease Control/ World Health Organization (NCDC/WHO) Map Resources for National Action Plan for Health Security (NAPHS) in 36 States and Federal Capital Territory (FCT)|date=2019-08-01|website=www.pulse.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2019/08/13/yellow-fever-outbreak-no-reagent-nigeria-government-sends-samples-cote-d%E2%80%99ivoire|title=Yellow Fever Outbreak: No Reagent In Nigeria, Government Sends Samples To Cote D\u2019Ivoire|last=siteadmin|date=2019-08-13|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> The agency is currently headed by [[Chikwe Ihekweazu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/cholera-ncdc-records-83-suspected-cases-in-adamawa/h8m7ddw|title=83 suspected cases of cholera recorded in Adamawa - NCDC|date=2019-08-22|website=www.pulse.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe main goal of the agency is to protect [[public health]] and safety through the control and prevention of communicable diseases in Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2019/08/13/yellow-fever-outbreak-no-reagent-nigeria-government-sends-samples-cote-d%E2%80%99ivoire|title=Yellow Fever Outbreak: No Reagent In Nigeria, Government Sends Samples To Cote D\u2019Ivoire|last=siteadmin|date=2019-08-13|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> The agency is also responsible for coordinating surveillance systems to collect, analyze and elucidate data gathered on diseases  of importance to the Nigerian community.\n\n== History ==\nThe idea for the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control Agency was conceived in 2011 where some departments in the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health]] was moved to help setup the agency. The departments at that time were Epidemiology Division, the [[Avian influenza|Avian Influenza]] Project and the Nigeria Field Epidemiology and Laboratory Training Programme. In November 2018, the bill of an act to establish Nigeria Centre for Disease Control was signed into law by President [[Muhammadu Buhari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/health/health-news/295424-buhari-signs-bill-establishing-nigeria-centre-for-disease-control.html|title=Buhari signs bill establishing Nigeria Centre for Disease Control|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|date=2018-11-13|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\nNCDC has a total of 217 staff led by the Director General of the agency. The Director general of the agency directly reports to the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health]] (Minister of Health).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.financialnigeria.com/buhari-signs-bill-to-establish-nigeria-centre-for-disease-control-news-1632.html|title=Buhari signs bill to establish Nigeria Centre for Disease Control|website=Financial Nigeria International Limited|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Federal Ministries of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Health ministries]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Health agency in Nigeria}}\n'''Nigeria Centre for Disease Control''' is Nigeria's leading [[National public health institutes|national public health institute]]. The NCDC is a Nigerian federal government agency under the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)]] and is headquartered in [[Abuja]], [[Nigeria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/apo/nigeria-centre-for-disease-control-world-health-organization-ncdcwho-map-resources/dw1ey3x|title=Nigeria Centre for Disease Control/ World Health Organization (NCDC/WHO) Map Resources for National Action Plan for Health Security (NAPHS) in 36 States and Federal Capital Territory (FCT)|date=2019-08-01|website=www.pulse.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2019/08/13/yellow-fever-outbreak-no-reagent-nigeria-government-sends-samples-cote-d%E2%80%99ivoire|title=Yellow Fever Outbreak: No Reagent In Nigeria, Government Sends Samples To Cote D\u2019Ivoire|last=siteadmin|date=2019-08-13|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> The agency is currently headed by [[Chikwe Ihekweazu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/cholera-ncdc-records-83-suspected-cases-in-adamawa/h8m7ddw|title=83 suspected cases of cholera recorded in Adamawa - NCDC|date=2019-08-22|website=www.pulse.ng|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\nThe main goal of the agency is to protect [[public health]] and safety through the control and prevention of communicable diseases in Nigeria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2019/08/13/yellow-fever-outbreak-no-reagent-nigeria-government-sends-samples-cote-d%E2%80%99ivoire|title=Yellow Fever Outbreak: No Reagent In Nigeria, Government Sends Samples To Cote D\u2019Ivoire|last=siteadmin|date=2019-08-13|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> The agency is also responsible for coordinating surveillance systems to collect, analyze and elucidate data gathered on diseases  of importance to the Nigerian community.\n\n== History ==\nThe idea for the Nigeria Centre for Disease Control Agency was conceived in 2011 where some departments in the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health]] was moved to help setup the agency. The departments at that time were Epidemiology Division, the Avian Influenza Project and the Nigeria Field Epidemiology and Laboratory Training Programme. In November 2018, the bill of an act to establish Nigeria Centre for Disease Control was signed into law by President [[Muhammadu Buhari]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/health/health-news/295424-buhari-signs-bill-establishing-nigeria-centre-for-disease-control.html|title=Buhari signs bill establishing Nigeria Centre for Disease Control|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|date=2018-11-13|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== Organization ==\nNCDC has a total of 217 staff led by the Director General of the agency. The Director general of the agency directly reports to the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|Federal Ministry of Health]] (Minister of Health).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.financialnigeria.com/buhari-signs-bill-to-establish-nigeria-centre-for-disease-control-news-1632.html|title=Buhari signs bill to establish Nigeria Centre for Disease Control|website=Financial Nigeria International Limited|language=en|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Federal Ministries of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organizations based in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Health ministries]]\n", "name_user": "Babbs61", "label": "safe", "comment": "Hyperlinked avian influenza", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigeria_Centre_for_Disease_Control"}
{"title_page": "Adolph Jentsch", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Adolph Jentsch\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image            = <!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size       =\n| alt              =\n| caption          =\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_lang =\n| birth_name       = Adolph Stephan Friedrich Jentsch\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1888|12|29}}\n\n| birth_place      = Deubell, [[Dresden]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1977|4|18|1888|12|29}}\n| death_place      =  [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]\n| resting_place    =   [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      =  [[Germany|German]]\n| education        =  Dresden Art Academy\n| known_for        =\n| notable_works    =\n| style            =\n| movement         =\n| spouse           =\n| awards           = 1913 K\u00f6niglich~S\u00e4chsische Staatsmedaille fur Kunst und Wissenschaft <br>\n1958 Order of Merit, First Class, Federal Republic of Germany<br>\n1962 Medal of Honour for Painting, S.A. Akademie vir Kuns en Wetenskap\n| elected          =\n| patrons          =\n| memorials        =\n| website          = {{URL|www.adolphjentsch.com}}\n| module           =\n}}\n\n'''Adolph Stephan Friedrich Jentsch''' (29 December 1888 [[Dresden]] \u2013 18 April 1977 [[Windhoek]]) was a [[Germany|German]]-born [[Namibia]]n artist. He studied at the Dresden ''Staatsakademie f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste'' ([[Dresden Art Academy]], today's ''College of Fine Arts'') for six years, and used a travel grant award to visit [[France]], [[Italy]], [[UK]] and the [[Netherlands]]. Jentsch moved to Namibia in 1938 to escape the approaching war and lived there until his death. He travelled extensively in Namibia and eventually settled down near Dordabis, about 60&nbsp;km from the capital [[Windhoek]].  He is one of Namibia's most famous painters.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Germany===\nJentsch was the son of a Lutheran church official, Stephan Jentsch, and his wife Adele.<ref name=\"ol\">{{cite book |last1=Levinson |first1=Olga |title=Adolph Jentsch |date=1973 |publisher=Human & Rousseau |location=Cape Town |isbn=9780798103060 }}</ref>  He attended the gymnasium of the ''Brudergemeine Zinzendorf'', at Nieski.<ref name=\"eb\">{{cite book |last1=Berman |first1=Esm\u00e9 |title=Art & Artists of South Africa: An Illustrated Biographical Dictionary and Historical Survey of Painters, Sculptors & Graphic Artists Since 1875 |date=1993 |publisher=Southern Book Publishers |location=South Africa |isbn=9781868123452}}</ref> Six years of further education followed at Dresden's ''Staatsakademie f\u03cbr Bildende K\u00fcnste''.<ref name=\"eb\" /> Other student artists at the Academy were Pechstein, Grosz and Schwitters.<ref name=\"ol\" /> He was awarded the ''K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsiche Staatsmedaille fur Kunst und Wissenschaft'' and several travel grants. Later, Jentsch often worked for Gussman, decorating public buildings.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch was in the [[J\u00e4ger (infantry)|J\u00e4ger-Reserve]] <ref name=\"eb\" /> in the First World War, but developed a crippling [[rheumatism]] that put him into a military hospital at [[Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe|Neustadt]] for a year.<ref name=\"ol\" /> After the war, he married a young divorcee, Anne Ilgen, in 1920, and together they operated a small factory making spray-containers for perfume. Anne ran the factory while Jentsch painted. A son, Christoph, was born in 1921.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch illustrated a children's book in 1927, and joined a group of interior decorators in [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"ol\" /> He worked on colour schemes and decorative painting on jobs in Germany and Czechoslovakia.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\n===Namibia===\nJentsch's antipathy to [[Nazism|National Socialism]] resulted in a loss of commissions, so he took up an offer to vacation on a friend's farm in Namibia (then called South West Africa). He arrived in Africa in early 1938, and never left, working in oils and watercolour until his death in 1977.\n\nJentsch painted landscapes almost exclusively, working in watercolour and oil. He was interested in Oriental philosophy, specifically [[Taoism]], and was influenced by Chinese Art. He travelled extensively in Namibia, staying at many farms and painting the diverse landscapes, but in 1947 he finally settled on a farm near Dordabis called ''Brack'', about 60&nbsp;km from Windhoek, with his friends Gebhard and Dorothee von Funcke.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch found the Namibian landscape amenable to his mystic approach to art. His watercolours display the same calligraphic strokes seen in Chinese art. In 1960 Jentsch abandoned oils and worked only in watercolour.<ref name=\"eb\" />\n\n===Later life===\nIn the early 1970s he suffered a [[stroke]] that left him with a severe tremor and stopped him painting completely. Jentsch and Dorothea von Funcke (whose husband had by now died) moved into a modest house in [[Windhoek]] for the last few years of his life.\n\nFive of his paintings were reproduced as stamps in 1973 \u2013 the first non-commemorative stamps in South Africa philatelic history.<ref name=\"eb\" />\n\nIn 1975, farm workers at ''Brack'', attempting to smoke out a wasp's nest, started a fire next to the old barn where Jentsch stored much of his oeuvre. The barn caught fire and burned down, with the result that the product of 40 years, including some of his most important works, was tragically lost.<ref name=\"ol\" /><ref name=\"eb\" />\n\nFour of Jentsch's watercolours were reproduced in limited editions by Orde Levinson in 1975.\n\n==Awards==\n*1913 K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsische Staatsmedaille f\u00fcr Kunst und Wissenschaft.\n*1958 [[Federal Cross of Merit|Order of Merit]], First Class, Federal Republic of West Germany.\n*1962 Medal of Honour for Painting, SA Akademie vir Wetenskap en Kuns.\n\n==Public Collections==\n*Administration of South West Africa\n*Hester Rupert Art Museum, Graaf-Reinet\n*Johannesburg Art Gallery\n*King George VI Gallery, Port Elizabeth\n*Pietersburg Collection\n*Pretoria Art Museum\n*Pretoria University\n*Rand Afrikaans University, Johannesburg\n*Rembrandt van Rijn Art Foundation\n*S.A Association of Arts, Windhoek\n*S.A National Gallery, Cape Town\n*South African National Art Gallery, Cape Town\n*State Museum, Windhoek\n*UNISA\n*University of Stellenbosch\n*William Humphreys Gallery, Kimberley.\n*{{AKL|77|535}}\n\n==Art Exhibitions==\n* 1938 : Adolph Jentsch's first one-man exhibition in Southern Africa, Windhoek.\n* 1954 : Venice Biennale\n* 1956 : First Quad of South African Art\n* 1958 : Retrospective Exhibition, Windhoek (70th Birthday); South African Exhibition touring Holland, Germany and Belgium.\n* 1960 Second Quad of South African Art.\n* 1962 : \u201cSouth West African Artists\u2019, South African National Art Gallery, Cape Town.\n* 1964 : Third Quad of South African Art.\n* 1966 : Republic Fest Exhibition, Pretoria.\n* 1967 : Prestige Exhibition, Johannesburg Art Gallery\n* 1968 : Retrospective Exhibition, SAAA, Windhoek (80th Birthday)\n* 1970/1 : Prestige Exhibition, Pretoria Art Museum\n* 1974 : Retrospective Exhibition, SAAA, Windhoek\n\n==Publications==\n*Adolph Jentsch. Die Bilder aus der Zigarrenkiste. 2003, by Peter Strack\n*Gallery Magazine, Autumn 1984, '''''Adolph Jentsch \u2014 Prayers in Paint''''' by Mark A. Meaker\n*Adolph Jentsch. 1973, by Olga Levinson\n*Lantern, Vol.3, No.4, April\u2013June, 1954: 'Adolph Jentsch' by Otto Schroder\n*Lantern, Vol.7, No.1, October, 1957: 'Vyf Kunstenaars uit Suidwes-Afrika'\n*Adolph Jentsch, SWA.: An appreciation with reproductions of watercolours painted by Jentsch in the surroundings of Brack. Essays by Otto Schroder and P. Anton Hendriks, Swakopmund, 1958 (70th anniversary)\n*Our Art, Vol.1: Essay by Otto Schroder, 1959\n*Fontein, Vol.1, No.1, 1960: 'Adolph Jentsch' by Anton Hendriks\n*Art in South Africa by F. L. Alexander, Cape Town, 1962\n*South West Africa Annual, 1970: 'Jentsch' by Olga Levinson\n*Art and artists of South Africa by Esme' Berman, Cape Town, 1970\n\n==Film==\n*Jentsch, documentary sound film, 16mm, commissioned by The Friends of the South African National Gallery, Cape Town, 1970. Written and produced by Olga Levinson; filmed by Lewis-Lewis Productions.\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adolphjentsch.com www.adolphjentsch.com] \u2014 Gallery of paintings, essays, photos of artist\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jentsch, Adolph}}\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:German male painters]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Landscape artists]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Namibia]]\n[[Category:White Namibian people]]\n[[Category:Namibian painters]]\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name             = Adolph Jentsch\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image            = <!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] -->\n| image_size       =\n| alt              =\n| caption          =\n| native_name      =\n| native_name_lang =\n| birth_name       = Adolph Stephan Friedrich Jentsch\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1888|12|29}}\n\n| birth_place      = Deubell, [[Dresden]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1977|4|18|1888|12|29}}\n| death_place      =  [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]\n| resting_place    =   [[Windhoek]], [[Namibia]]\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      =  [[Germany|German]]\n| education        =  Dresden Art Academy\n| known_for        =\n| notable_works    =\n| style            =\n| movement         =\n| spouse           =\n| awards           = 1913 K\u00f6niglich~S\u00e4chsische Staatsmedaille fur Kunst und Wissenschaft <br>\n1958 Order of Merit, First Class, Federal Republic of Germany<br>\n1962 Medal of Honour for Painting, S.A. Akademie vir Kuns en Wetenskap\n| elected          =\n| patrons          =\n| memorials        =\n| website          = {{URL|www.adolphjentsch.com}}\n| module           =\n}}\n\n'''Adolph Stephan Friedrich Jentsch''' (29 December 1888 [[Dresden]] \u2013 18 April 1977 [[Windhoek]]) was a [[Germany|German]]-born [[Namibia]]n artist. He studied at the Dresden ''Staatsakademie f\u00fcr Bildende Kunste'' ([[Dresden Art Academy]], today's ''College of Fine Arts'') for six years, and used a travel grant award to visit [[France]], [[Italy]], [[UK]] and the [[Netherlands]]. Jentsch moved to Namibia in 1938 to escape the approaching war and lived there until his death. He travelled extensively in Namibia and eventually settled down near Dordabis, about 60&nbsp;km from the capital [[Windhoek]].  He is one of Namibia's most famous painters.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Germany===\nJentsch was the son of a Lutheran church official, Stephan Jentsch, and his wife Adele.<ref name=\"ol\">{{cite book |last1=Levinson |first1=Olga |title=Adolph Jentsch |date=1973 |publisher=Human & Rousseau |location=Cape Town |isbn=9780798103060 }}</ref>  He attended the gymnasium of the ''Brudergemeine Zinzendorf'', at Nieski.<ref name=\"eb\">{{cite book |last1=Berman |first1=Esm\u00e9 |title=Art & Artists of South Africa: An Illustrated Biographical Dictionary and Historical Survey of Painters, Sculptors & Graphic Artists Since 1875 |date=1993 |publisher=Southern Book Publishers |location=South Africa |isbn=9781868123452}}</ref> Six years of further education followed at Dresden's ''Staatsakademie f\u03cbr Bildende K\u00fcnste''.<ref name=\"eb\" /> Other student artists at the Academy were Pechstein, Grosz and Schwitters.<ref name=\"ol\" /> He was awarded the ''K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsiche Staatsmedaille fur Kunst und Wissenschaft'' and several travel grants. Later, Jentsch often worked for Gussman, decorating public buildings.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch was in the [[J\u00e4ger (infantry)|J\u00e4ger-Reserve]] <ref name=\"eb\" /> in the First World War, but developed a crippling [[rheumatism]] that put him into a military hospital at [[Neustadt an der Weinstra\u00dfe|Neustadt]] for a year.<ref name=\"ol\" /> After the war, he married a young divorcee, Anne Ilgen, in 1920, and together they operated a small factory making spray-containers for perfume. Anne ran the factory while Jentsch painted. A son, Christoph, was born in 1921.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch illustrated a children's book in 1927, and joined a group of interior decorators in [[Czechoslovakia]].<ref name=\"ol\" /> He worked on colour schemes and decorative painting on jobs in Germany and Czechoslovakia.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\n===Namibia===\nJentsch's antipathy to [[Nazism|National Socialism]] resulted in a loss of commissions, so he took up an offer to vacation on a friend's farm in Namibia (then called South West Africa). He arrived in Africa in early 1938, and never left, working in oils and watercolour until his death in 1977.\n\nJentsch painted landscapes almost exclusively, working in watercolour and oil. He was interested in Oriental philosophy, specifically [[Taoism]], and was influenced by Chinese Art. He travelled extensively in Namibia, staying at many farms and painting the diverse landscapes, but in 1947 he finally settled on a farm near Dordabis called ''Brack'', about 60&nbsp;km from Windhoek, with his friends Gebhard and Dorothee von Funcke.<ref name=\"ol\" />\n\nJentsch found the Namibian landscape amenable to his mystic approach to art. His watercolours display the same calligraphic strokes seen in Chinese art. In 1960 Jentsch abandoned oils and worked only in watercolour.<ref name=\"eb\" />\n\n===Later life===\nIn the early 1970s he suffered a [[stroke]] that left him with a severe tremor and stopped him painting completely. Jentsch and Dorothea von Funcke (whose husband had by now died) moved into a modest house in [[Windhoek]] for the last few years of his life.\n\nFive of his paintings were reproduced as stamps in 1973 \u2013 the first non-commemorative stamps in South Africa philatelic history.<ref name=\"eb\" />\n\nIn 1975, farm workers at ''Brack'', attempting to smoke out a wasp's nest, started a fire next to the old barn where Jentsch stored much of his oeuvre. The barn caught fire and burned down, with the result that the product of 40 years, including some of his most important works, was tragically lost.<ref name=\"ol\" /><ref name=\"eb\" />\n\nFour of Jentsch's watercolours were reproduced in limited editions by Orde Levinson in 1975.\n\n==Awards==\n*1913 K\u00f6niglich-S\u00e4chsische Staatsmedaille f\u00fcr Kunst und Wissenschaft.\n*1958 [[Federal Cross of Merit|Order of Merit]], First Class, Federal Republic of West Germany.\n*1962 Medal of Honour for Painting, SA Akademie vir Wetenskap en Kuns.\n\n==Public Collections==\n*Administration of South West Africa\n*Hester Rupert Art Museum, Graaf-Reinet\n*Johannesburg Art Gallery\n*King George VI Gallery, Port Elizabeth\n*Pietersburg Collection\n*Pretoria Art Museum\n*Pretoria University\n*Rand Afrikaans University, Johannesburg\n*Rembrandt van Rijn Art Foundation\n*S.A Association of Arts, Windhoek\n*S.A National Gallery, Cape Town\n*South African National Art Gallery, Cape Town\n*State Museum, Windhoek\n*UNISA\n*University of Stellenbosch\n*William Humphreys Gallery, Kimberley.\n*{{AKL|77|535}}\n\n==Art Exhibitions==\n* 1938 : Adolph Jentsch's first one-man exhibition in Southern Africa, Windhoek.\n* 1954 : Venice Biennale\n* 1956 : First Quad of South African Art\n* 1958 : Retrospective Exhibition, Windhoek (70th Birthday); South African Exhibition touring Holland, Germany and Belgium.\n* 1960 Second Quad of South African Art.\n* 1962 : \u201cSouth West African Artists\u2019, South African National Art Gallery, Cape Town.\n* 1964 : Third Quad of South African Art.\n* 1966 : Republic Fest Exhibition, Pretoria.\n* 1967 : Prestige Exhibition, Johannesburg Art Gallery\n* 1968 : Retrospective Exhibition, SAAA, Windhoek (80th Birthday)\n* 1970/1 : Prestige Exhibition, Pretoria Art Museum\n* 1974 : Retrospective Exhibition, SAAA, Windhoek\n\n==Publications==\n*Adolph Jentsch. Die Bilder aus der Zigarrenkiste. 2003, by Peter Strack\n*Gallery Magazine, Autumn 1984, '''''Adolph Jentsch \u2014 Prayers in Paint''''' by Mark A. Meaker\n*Adolph Jentsch. 1973, by Olga Levinson\n*Lantern, Vol.3, No.4, April\u2013June, 1954: 'Adolph Jentsch' by Otto Schroder\n*Lantern, Vol.7, No.1, October, 1957: 'Vyf Kunstenaars uit Suidwes-Afrika'\n*Adolph Jentsch, SWA.: An appreciation with reproductions of watercolours painted by Jentsch in the surroundings of Brack. Essays by Otto Schroder and P. Anton Hendriks, Swakopmund, 1958 (70th anniversary)\n*Our Art, Vol.1: Essay by Otto Schroder, 1959\n*Fontein, Vol.1, No.1, 1960: 'Adolph Jentsch' by Anton Hendriks\n*Art in South Africa by F. L. Alexander, Cape Town, 1962\n*South West Africa Annual, 1970: 'Jentsch' by Olga Levinson\n*Art and artists of South Africa by Esme' Berman, Cape Town, 1970\n\n==Film==\n*Jentsch, documentary sound film, 16mm, commissioned by The Friends of the South African National Gallery, Cape Town, 1970. Written and produced by Olga Levinson; filmed by Lewis-Lewis Productions.\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adolphjentsch.com www.adolphjentsch.com] \u2014 Gallery of paintings, essays, photos of artist\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jentsch, Adolph}}\n[[Category:20th-century German painters]]\n[[Category:German male painters]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Landscape artists]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to Namibia]]\n[[Category:White Namibian people]]\n[[Category:Namibian painters]]\n[[Category:1888 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Satzko.geni", "label": "safe", "comment": "One more try (my other corrections were accepted): If you click on 'Dresden Art Academy' then 'Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K-\u00fc-nste Dresden' will show up (text in the Englisch Wikipedia). Thus it should be K-\u00fc-nste and not K-u-nste?", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolph_Jentsch"}
{"title_page": "Kim Seok-jin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{short description|South Korean singer}}\n{{Korean name|Kim}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = World wide handsome\n| image              = Jin for Dispatch \"Boy With Luv\" MV behind the scene shooting, 15 March 2019 01 (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Kim on the set of the \"[[Boy with Luv]]\" music video, March 2019\n| alt                = Kim in a white suit against a yellow purple and red bokeh background, he looks upwards and right\n| native_name        = \uae40\uc11d\uc9c4\n| other_names        = Jin <!-- Only names that were used professionally. Don't put nicknames here. -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1992|12|4}}\n| birth_place        = [[Gwacheon]], [[Gyeonggi-do]], South Korea\n| education          = [[Konkuk University]]<!-- Universities he's GRADUATED from. And don't mention what he studied here; put that in the body. -->\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter}}\n| awards             = [[File:ROK_Order_of_Cultural_Merit_Hwa-gwan_(5th_Class)_ribbon.PNG|border|23px]] [[Order of Cultural Merit (Korea)|Hwagwan Order of Cultural Merit]] (2018)\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| net_worth          = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[pop-rock]]}}<!-- Genres for his solo songs. -->\n| instrument         = Vocals <!-- Only what he's known for, not what he's capable of! -->\n| label              = [[Big Hit Entertainment|Big Hit]]\n| associated_acts    = [[BTS]]}}\n| website            = \n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name\n| child              = yes\n| title              = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul             = {{Korean|hangul=\uae40\uc11d\uc9c4|labels=no}}\n| hanja              = {{linktext|\u91d1|\u78a9|\u73cd}}\n| rr                 = Gim Seok-jin\n| mr                 = Kim S\u014fkchin\n}}\n| signature          = \n}}\n\n'''Kim Seok-jin''' ({{Korean|\uae40\uc11d\uc9c4}}; born on December 4, 1992), also known by his stage name '''Jin''', is a South Korean singer and songwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.search.naver.com/search.naver?where=nexearch&query=%EC%A7%84&sm=ppl_cts&ie=utf8&key=PeopleService&os=585546|title=\uc9c4 \ud504\ub85c\ud544|date=May 14, 2018|website=people.search.naver.com|publisher=Naver|language=ko|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"bbjinprofile\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7850038/bts-jin-get-to-know|title=Get to Know BTS: Jin|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=June 30, 2017|website=Billboard|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref> He is a member and vocalist of the [[Korean pop idol|South Korean boy group]] [[BTS]].<ref name=\"bbjinprofile\" />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKim Seok-jin was born on December 4, 1992, in [[Gwacheon]], [[Gyeonggi Province]], South Korea.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/music/article/2158784/jin-k-pop-superband-bts-his-past-his-private-thoughts-and-why-hes|title=Jin from K-pop superband BTS: his past, his private thoughts and why he\u2019s called \u2018Car Door Guy\u2019|last=Tai|first=Crystal|date=August 11, 2018|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|access-date=October 9, 2018}}</ref> His family consists of his mother, father and older brother.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestar.chosun.com/m/view.html?query=%EB%B3%B4%EC%9D%B4%EA%B7%B8%EB%A3%B9%20%EC%84%9C%EC%97%B4&contid=2015043001449|last=Jang|first=Eun-kyung|date=April 30, 2015|website=[[The Chosun Ilbo|The Star]]|publisher=Chosun Ilb so Company|language=ko|script-title=ko:[\ub354\uc2a4\ud0c0\ud504\ub85c\ud544] \ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4 \"\uc81c\uac00 \uc815\ub9d0 \uc798\uc0dd\uacbc\uc744\uae4c\uc694?\"|accessdate=July 5, 2018|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001104214/http://thestar.chosun.com/m/view.html?query=%EB%B3%B4%EC%9D%B4%EA%B7%B8%EB%A3%B9%20%EC%84%9C%EC%97%B4&contid=2015043001449|archive-date=October 1, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n \nWhile in junior high school, Kim was [[talent scouting|scouted]] by South Korean [[K-pop]] agency [[SM Entertainment]] off the street, but he rejected the offer at the time.<ref name=\"ajunews\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ajunews.com/view/20190522140732606|title=[BTS \uc5bc\ub9c8\ub098 \uc544\uc2ed\ub2c8\uae4c] \uc778\ubb3c\ud0d0\uad6c\u2461 \ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc11c\ube0c\ubcf4\uceec '\uc9c4'|date=May 23, 2019|accessdate=May 24, 2019|work=Aju News|last=Choi|first=Song-hye|language=ko}}</ref> He initially intended to be an actor, attending [[Konkuk University]] and graduating with a degree in art and acting on February 22, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thestar.chosun.com/m/view.html?query=%EB%B3%B4%EC%9D%B4%EA%B7%B8%EB%A3%B9%20%EC%84%9C%EC%97%B4&contid=2015043001449|last=Jang|first=Eun-kyung|date=April 30, 2015|website=[[The Chosun Ilbo|The Star]]|publisher=Chosun Ilbo Company|language=ko|script-title=ko:[\ub354\uc2a4\ud0c0\ud504\ub85c\ud544] \ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4 \"\uc81c\uac00 \uc815\ub9d0 \uc798\uc0dd\uacbc\uc744\uae4c\uc694?\"|accessdate=July 6, 2018|title=Archived copy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001104214/http://thestar.chosun.com/m/view.html?query=%EB%B3%B4%EC%9D%B4%EA%B7%B8%EB%A3%B9%20%EC%84%9C%EC%97%B4&contid=2015043001449|archive-date=October 1, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Kong>{{cite web|url=https://www.studyinternational.com/news/college-k-pop-stardom-education-helped-multi-talented-performers/#40EAu5ptDX9l3Kae.97|title=From college to K-pop stardom: How education helped these multi-talented performers|last=Kong|first=Leelian|date=March 21, 2017|website=studyinternational.com|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref> He enrolled in graduate school at [[Hanyang Cyber University]], to pursue studies in areas other than music.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201703021759160392034_2|title=Jin of BTS, Chen of EXO enter graduate school at Hanyang Cyber University|last=Kim|first=So-yeon|date=March 2, 2017|work=Kpop Herald|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 2013\u2013present: BTS ===\n{{Main|BTS}}\nKim was scouted by [[Big Hit Entertainment]] for his looks while walking down the street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/inside-bts-mania-a-day-in-the-life-of-the-k-pop-superstars-129689/|title=Inside BTS-mania: A Day in the Life of the K-Pop Superstars|last=Martins|first=Chris|date=December 19, 2017|website=Rolling Stone|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> At the time Kim was studying acting and had no background in music.<ref name=\"bbjinprofile\" /><ref name=Kong/> Subsequently, he auditioned for Big Hit as an actor before becoming an [[Korean idol#Trainee system|idol trainee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://stylecaster.com/how-bts-members-discovered/#slide-4|title=BTS\u2019s 7 Members Were Discovered in the Most Unconventional Ways|work=StyleCaster|date=2019|accessdate=January 12, 2020|last=Pham|first=Jason}}</ref> On June 13, 2013, Kim made his debut as one of the four vocalists in BTS with their debut [[single album]] ''[[2 Cool 4 Skool]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/upstream/bts-kpop-korean-boy-band/|title=How BTS is changing K-pop for the better|last=Bennett|first=Colette|date=May 12, 2016|website=dailydot|accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref> Kim released his first co-produced track, a solo single from the album ''[[Wings (BTS album)|Wings]]'' titled \"Awake\", in 2016.<ref name=\"bbjinprofile\" /> The song peaked at number 31 on the [[Gaon Music Chart]] and six on the Billboard World Digital Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?serviceGbn=S1020&termGbn=week&hitYear=2017&targetTime=07&nationGbn=K|title=2017\ub144 07\uc8fc\ucc28 Download Chart|work=Gaon Music Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|language=Korean|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2016-10-29/world-digital-songs|title=World Digital Songs (October 29, 2016)|magazine=Billboard|access-date=July 7, 2018}}</ref> In December 2016, he released a Christmas version of \"Awake\" on [[SoundCloud]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn August 9, 2018, the second solo by Kim, \"[[Epiphany (BTS song)|Epiphany]]\", was released as a trailer for BTS' then-upcoming compilation album ''[[Love Yourself: Answer]]''. The song was described as a \"building [[pop-rock]] melody\" by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' and contains lyrics discussing self-acceptance and self-love.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8469473/bts-epiphany-comeback-trailer-jin-sings-video|title=BTS' Jin Sings in 'Epiphany' Comeback Trailer Ahead Of 'Love Yourself: Answer' Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 9, 2018|last=Herman|first=Tamar|accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref> The full version of the song was eventually released as a track on ''Answer'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/bts-jin-takes-center-stage-in-epiphany-comeback-trailer-ahead-of-new-album-107670|title=BTS' Jin Takes Center Stage in 'Epiphany' Comeback Trailer Ahead of New Album|last=Drysdale|first=Jennifer|date=August 9, 2018|website=Entertainment Tonight|access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref> peaking at number 30 on the Gaon Music Chart and four on the ''Billboard'' World Digital Singles Chart.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\">Awake: {{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2016-10-29/world-digital-songs|title=World Digital Songs (October 29, 2016)|magazine=Billboard}}</ref> In October, he was awarded the fifth-class Hwagwan [[Order of Cultural Merit (Korea)|Order of Cultural Merit]] by South Korean president [[Moon Jae-in]] along with other members of the group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=312&aid=0000354692|title='\ub300\uc911\ubb38\ud654\uc608\uc220\uc0c1' BTS, \ubb38\ud654\ud6c8\uc7a5 \ud654\uad00 \ucd5c\uc5f0\uc18c \uc218\ud6c8...\uc720\uc7ac\uc11d\ubd80\ud130 \u6545 \uae40\uc8fc\ud601\uae4c\uc9c0 '\uc601\uad11\uc758 \uc5bc\uad74\ub4e4' (\uc885\ud569)|access-date=2018-10-25|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n=== 2015\u2013present: Solo activities ===\nKim collaborated with fellow BTS member [[V (singer)|V]] on the song \"It's Definitely You\", released as part of the ''[[Hwarang: The Poet Warrior Youth]]'' original soundtrack.<ref>\n{{Cite web|url=http://m.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201611270949080410|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\ud6a8\ub9b0 \uc591\uc694\uc12d \ubc29\ud0c4 \ubdd4X\uc9c4 '\ud654\ub791' OST \uc9c0\uc6d0\uc0ac\uaca9 '\uba85\ud488\ubcf4\uceec \ucd1d\ucd9c\ub3d9'|date=November 27, 2016|website=m.newsen.com|language=Korean|access-date=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003450160|title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \ubdd4X\uc9c4, '\ud654\ub791'OST \ub450\ubc88\uc9f8 \uc8fc\uc790 \ucd9c\uaca9\u2026\uc624\ub298 \uc790\uc815 \uacf5\uac1c|last=|first=|date=December 19, 2016|work=OSEN|access-date=July 8, 2018|language=ko}}</ref> He also joined BTS member Jungkook to sing and release an alternate version of \"So Far Away\", a song from BTS member [[Suga (rapper)|Suga]]'s self-titled mixtape ''Agust D''.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8459916/bts-jin-in-front-of-the-post-office-in-autumn-cover|title=BTS' Jin Releases Cover of 'In Front of the Post Office in Autumn': Listen|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=June 7, 2017|website=billboard.com|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref> Kim's solo covers include \"Mom\" by [[Ra.D]], \"I Love You\" by Mate, and \"In Front Of The Post Office In Autumn\", originally by [[Yoon Do-hyun]] in 1994.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8099026/bts-covers|title=7 BTS Covers You Should Listen To|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=February 9, 2018|website=billboard.com|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.koogle.tv/media/news/bangtan-boys-jin-reveals-cover-of-i-love-you-by-mate/|title=Bangtan Boys\u2019 Jin Reveals Cover of \u2018I Love You\u2019 by Mate|last=Song|first=Michael|date=December 3, 2015|work=koogle.tv|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/bts-jin-covers-korean-rock-ballad-debut-track-yoon-do-hyun|title=BTS' Jin Covers Korean Rock Ballad, Debut Track Of Yoon Do-hyun|last=Merrill|first=Philip|date=June 8, 2018|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|accessdate=July 6, 2018}}</ref> They were released on SoundCloud on May 7, 2015,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/bangtan/150507mp3|title=\uc5c4\ub9c8 (cover) by Jin|date=May 7, 2015|website=soundcloud|access-date=July 9, 2018}}</ref> December 3, 2015,<ref name=\":5\" /> and June 7, 2018,<ref name=\":4\" /> respectively. He has also made several appearances as a co-host for Korean music award shows, such as [[Music Bank (TV series)|''Music Bank'']] and ''[[Inkigayo]]''.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nOn June 4, 2019, Kim released his first independent song \"Tonight\" as part of the 2019 BTS Festa, a yearly event celebrating the anniversary of the band's debut.<ref name=Tonight>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-tonight-first-solo-song-bts-jin-2504785|title=Listen to 'Tonight', the first solo song by BTS' Jin|last=Daly|first=Rhian|date=June 4, 2019|work=[[NME]]|access-date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> The [[Acoustic music|acoustic]] ballad was composed by Kim, alongside Big Hit Entertainment [[record producer]]s Slow Rabbit and Hiss Noise. The lyrics, written by Kim and BTS leader [[RM (rapper)|RM]],<ref>{{cite AV media|date=June 6, 2019|language=ko|accessdate=May 23, 2019|location=[[V Live (website)|V Live]]|publisher=[[Naver]]|url=https://www.vlive.tv/video/133130|title=TS Live : \ubbf8\ub2c8\ubaa8\ub2c8}}</ref> are inspired by Kim's relationship with his pets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bts/8514454/jin-tonight-new-song|title=BTS' Jin Releases Poignant Solo Track 'Tonight': Listen|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref> The track was met with a generally positive reception, with praise for Kim's vocals and the song's calming atmosphere.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/1046904/bts-jin-releases-emotional-|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|work=[[E!]]|last=Contreras|first=Cydney|title=BTS' Jin Releases Emotional Solo Single In Honor of Their 2019 Festa}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[File:Kim Seok-jin at the 2018 Korean Popular Culture & Arts Awards (3) (cropped).jpg|Kim at the [[Korean Popular Culture and Arts Awards]] on October 24, 2018.|thumb|upright|alt=Kim, wearing a formal black suit at an award ceremony, waves to the crowd]]\nKim is a [[tenor]] and can play the guitar.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/music/2019/06/04/bts-jin-solo-song-tonight-pets/|title=Listen to BTS star Kim's new solo song 'Tonight,' a heartwarming ode to his pets|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=June 4, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|last=Vollero|first=Lexi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-jin-from-bts-mr-worldwide-handsome-will-take-your-breath-away-with-his-talent-12077646|title=Who Is Jin From BTS? Mr. Worldwide Handsome Will Take Your Breath Away With His Talent|work=Elite Daily|last=Martinez|first=Tara|date=September 27, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref> Critically, his singing voice has received a generally positive reception. In Kim Young-dae's 2019 novel ''BTS: The Review'', members of the [[Grammy Awards|Grammy]] panel stated that his voice has stable breath control and a strong [[falsetto]], calling it a \"silver voice\".<ref>{{cite book|title=BTS - The Review: A Comprehensive Look at the Music of BTS|last=Kim|first=Young-dae|publisher=RH Korea|year=2019|isbn=9788925565828|location=Seoul}}</ref> Journalist Choi Song-hye, writing for ''Aju News'', wrote that BTS singles such as \"[[Spring Day (BTS song)|Spring Day]]\" and \"[[Fake Love (BTS song)|Fake Love]]\" displayed Kim's vocal stability, while the b-side \"[[Map of the Soul: Persona|Jamais Vu]]\" did so for his emotional range.<ref name=\"ajunews\" /> Hong Hye-min of ''[[The Korea Times (Los Angeles)|The Korea Times]]'' described Kim's voice as \"tender, sorrowful, [and] free-spirited\" and considered it to be the \"standout element\" on the solo ballad \"Epiphany\".<ref>{{cite news|language=ko|title=\"\uc0ac\ub791\ud558\uace0 \uc2f6\uc5b4\"...\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4, \ub9ac\ud328\ud0a4\uc9c0 \ucef4\ubc31 \ud2b8\ub808\uc77c\ub7ec 'Epiphany' \uc8fc\uc778\uacf5|work=[[The Korea Times]]|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=469&aid=0000320775|last=Hong|first=Hye-min|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=June 4, 2018}}</ref> Critic Park Hee-a, when discussing \"Epiphany\", stated that Kim \"sings the most sentimental emotions\" of the solo tracks on ''Love Yourself: Answer''. In a review of \"Fake Love\", Park said that Kim's belting \"prove[d] [the song's] effectiveness\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreanmusicawards.com/2019/project/%EB%B0%A9%ED%83%84%EC%86%8C%EB%85%84%EB%8B%A8-bts-fake-love/|title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 (BTS) \u00b4FAKE LOVE\u00b4|language=ko|publisher=[[Korean Music Awards]]|last=Park|first=Hee-a}}</ref>\n\n== Influence ==\nIn 2018, he was ranked as the 11th most well-known [[Korean idol|idol]] in South Korea, via data collected by analytics company [[Gallup (company)|Gallup Korea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\ud55c\uad6d\uac24\ub7fd \ub370\uc77c\ub9ac \uc624\ud53c\ub2c8\uc5b8, \ub9e4\uc8fc \uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \uc5ec\ub860\uc870\uc0ac \uacb0\uacfc\ub97c \uc804\ud569\ub2c8\ub2e4. |url=https://gallupkorea.blogspot.com/2018/12/2018-12_18.html |website=Gallop Korea |accessdate=December 18, 2018 |language=Korean |date=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nIn December 2018, Kim donated various supplies to the Korean Animal Welfare Association to celebrate his birthday, purchasing food, blankets, and dishes for the organization.<ref>References:\n*{{cite web |last1=Hwang |first1=Hye-jin |title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uce21 \"\uc9c4, \uc0dd\uc77c \ub9de\uc544 \uc720\uae30\uacac \uc0ac\ub8cc \uc9c1\uc811 \uad6c\uc785+\uae30\ubd80\"(\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5) |url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=609&aid=0000025967 |work=Newsen |accessdate=December 4, 2018 |language=Korean |date=December 4, 2018}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=018&aid=0004266040|title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4, \uc0dd\uc77c \ub9de\uc544 \uc720\uae30\uacac\ubcf4\ud638\uc18c\uc5d0 \ubb3c\ud488 \uae30\ubd80 '\ud6c8\ud6c8'|work=E Daily|last=Jeong|first=Si-nae|date=December 4, 2018|accessdate=December 9, 2018}}</ref> He also donated 321 kilograms of food to the [[Korea Animal Rights Advocates]] (KARA), another Korean animal welfare non-profit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sbs.co.kr/news/endPage.do?news_id=N1005045004&plink=ORI&cooper=NAVER|title=[\uc2a4\ube0c\uc2a4\ud0c0] \uc0dd\uc77c \uae30\ub150\ud574 \uc720\uae30\ub3d9\ubb3c\uc5d0 \uc0ac\ub8cc 321kg \ud6c4\uc6d0\ud55c '\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8' \uc9c4|date=December 5, 2018|accessdate=December 9, 2018|work=[[SBS News]]|last=Lee|first=Sun-young}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2018, Kim has been a monthly donor to [[UNICEF|UNICEF Korea]], requesting that his donations be kept private at the time. They were eventually publicized following his induction into the UNICEF Honors Club in May 2019 for donating over [[South Korean won|\u20a9]]100 million (about [[United States dollar|US$]]84,000).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unicef.or.kr/news/press_view.asp?idx=100575&trackcode=jin_honors_twt|title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4 \ub204\uc801 \uc720\ub2c8\uc138\ud504 \uae30\ubd80\uae08 1\uc5b5 \uc774\uc0c1, \u2018\uc544\ub108\uc2a4\ud074\ub7fd\u2019 \ud68c\uc6d0 \ub410\ub2e4|language=ko|publisher=[[UNICEF|UNICEF Korea]]|date=May 31, 2019|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nAs of 2018, Kim lives in [[Hannam-dong]], [[Seoul]], South Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=101&oid=025&aid=0002833392|title=[\ub77c\uc774\ud504\ud2b8\ub80c\ub4dc] \uc720\uba85\uc778\uc774 \ubc18\ud55c \ud55c\ub0a8\ub3d9, \ucd5c\uace0\uae09 \uc8fc\uac70\uc9c0\ub85c \ub72c \uc774\uc720|work=[[Korea JoongAng Daily]]|language=ko|date=July 3, 2018|access-date=August 17, 2018|last=Han|first=Jin}}</ref> In 2018, Kim purchased a luxury apartment in South Korea worth US$1.7 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moon |first1=Yong-gyoon |title=\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8 \uc9c4 60\uc5b5 \ud638\ud654\uc219\uc18c \uc606 20\uc5b5 \uac1c\uc778\ube4c\ub77c \uc0c0\ub2e4 |url=http://www.skyedaily.com/news/news_view.html?ID=79013 |website=Skyedaily |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |language=Korean |date=November 17, 2018}}</ref> Despite owning an apartment, he continues to live with the members of BTS in Hannam-dong.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hwang |first1=Bi |title=34\uc5b5\uc9dc\ub9ac \uace0\uae09 \ube4c\ub77c \ub300\ucd9c \uc5c6\uc774 '\ud604\uae08'\uc73c\ub85c \ub9e4\uc785\ud55c '\uc601\uc564\ub9ac\uce58' \ubc29\ud0c4 \uc288\uac00 |url=https://www.insight.co.kr/news/205691 |website=Insight |accessdate=April 3, 2019 |language=Korean |date=January 20, 2019}}</ref> Additionally, he and his older brother opened a Japanese-style restaurant in Seoul called Ossu Seiromushi in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tai |first1=Crystal |url=https://www.scmp.com/culture/music/article/2158784/jin-k-pop-superband-bts-his-past-his-private-thoughts-and-why-hes |title=Jin from K-pop superband BTS: his past, his private thoughts and why he\u2019s called \u2018Car Door Guy\u2019 |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=17 October 2018 |date=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{for|Kim's accolades as a member of BTS|List of awards and nominations received by BTS}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n|+Name of the award ceremony, year presented, nominee(s) of the award, award category, and the result of the nomination\n! scope=\"col\" | Award ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominee(s)/work(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|[[Melon Music Awards]]\n| [[2017 Melon Music Awards|2017]]\n| Best {{abbr|OST|original soundtrack}}\n| {{sort|It's Definitely You|\"[[Hwarang: The Poet Warrior Youth|It's Definitely You]]\"}}\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/kwave/2016/11/19/16/3001000000AEN20161119003200315F.html|title=BTS, EXO, TWICE top 2016 Melon Music Awards|last=Chung|first=Joo-won|date=November 20, 2016|work=[[Yonhap News Agency|Yonhap News]]|url-status=live|access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Discography == \n{{For|Kim's works with BTS|BTS singles discography|BTS albums discography}}\n\n=== Charted songs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" | Year\n! colspan=\"7\" scope=\"col\" | Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" | Sales\n! rowspan=\"3\" scope=\"col\" | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| KOR\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:3.5em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard charts|US World]]<br><ref>Compiled US World sources:\n* Awake: {{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/2016-10-29/world-digital-songs|title=World Digital Songs (October 29, 2016)|magazine=Billboard}}\n* It's Definitely You: {{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7669823/clc-hobgoblin-world-digital-song-sales-albums-charts-first-appearance|t